  "prompt": "How do flu vaccines work?",
  "response": "Flu vaccines work by introducing your body to a harmless piece of the flu virus or a weakened form of the virus itself. This triggers your immune system to produce antibodies to fight the virus. These antibodies remain in your body, providing protection if you are exposed to the flu virus in the future.\n\nThere are several types of flu vaccines, including:\n\n1. Inactivated flu vaccine: This is the most common type of flu vaccine. It's made from killed flu viruses and is given as an injection.\n\n2. Recombinant flu vaccine: This type of vaccine is made without using flu viruses. Instead, scientists use a process that involves growing the virus's hemagglutinin (HA) protein in insect cells. The HA protein is then purified and used to make the vaccine.\n\n3. Live attenuated influenza vaccine (LAIV): This vaccine is made from weakened live flu viruses and is given as a nasal spray.\n\nThe flu virus changes from year to year, so the vaccine is updated annually to include the strains of the virus that are predicted to be most common. It's recommended that everyone over the age of 6 months get a flu vaccine every year to protect against the flu and its potential complications.",
